@ people going berserk about the ad
I get it, it's a multinational corporation, it must have propaganda. It has been accused of child labour. I'm not saying Gillette is any good, I definitely don't think so. But, what's pissing me off is that people can't stop with their "not all men", "get your act together first". I mean, there's a billion commercial out there about men's products where they are literally fetishising women and objectifying them to the worst levels possible. I don't see you saying "not all men" to that. Why is it only normal to you when it's women getting objectified and when you're asked to just be a good person by cutting off the toxic masculinity, suddenly you feel attacked? Is it that toxic masculinity that the ad was talking about? 
And Gillette was accused of child labour in 2016 so, if so many of you genuinely cared about child labour, how are they still in the market??

We want you to do us a little favour - check out the new Gillette ad about toxic masculinity on YouTube, and then go through the comments - we bet most of you would be shocked at the kind of hate this advertisement is getting - yes, we agree that it's a little too simplistic a take on toxic masculinity, but - look at the number of men going mad about "a commercial brand teaching them manners".
Ironically, this is where toxic masculinity really comes into the picture - when you're asked to behave, your defenses rake up with "who are you to tell me what to do", or "not all men", and "now I'll have to get a moral lecture from YOUR KIND!"
There are days when it's just futile to initiate a conversation about anything, because the person on the other end enjoys behaving deaf.
Our men have been stereotyped too like our women...for too long now...for too long
